\begin_layout Subsubsection
Navier-Stokes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume an incompressible water body.
 The derivation works with the velocity potential and the stream function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\nabla\phi+\nabla\times\psi$
\end_inset

.
 For an irrotational fluid,
 of course,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=0$
\end_inset

.
 Navier-Stokes equations then take the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{t}v & =-\nabla\left(\frac{1}{\rho}p+gz\right)+\nu\nabla^{2}v\\
\implies\nabla\partial_{t}\phi+\nabla\times\partial_{t}\psi & =-\nabla\left(\frac{1}{\rho}p+gz\right)+\nu\nabla\times\left(\nabla^{2}\psi\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we use the incompressibility condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We require that the two components of the velocity field take care separately for each physical effect:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nabla\partial_{t}\phi & =-\nabla\left(\frac{1}{\rho}p+gz\right),\\
\nabla\times\partial_{t}\psi & =\nu\nabla\times\left(\nabla^{2}\psi\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Clearly it is enough to demand that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\partial_{t}\phi & =-\left(\frac{1}{\rho}\left(p-p_{0}\right)+gz\right),\label{eq:navier-stokes}\\
\partial_{t}\psi & =\nu\nabla^{2}\psi,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we in practice chose a gauge.
 In the following I denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta p=p-p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
In the following I will abuse 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

,
 treating it as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 component of the vector potential - essentially a stream function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Concentration modeling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have two conservation of matter equation and one boundary condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{t}c & =D\left(\partial_{x}^{2}c+\partial_{z}^{2}c\right),\\
\partial_{t}s & =-\partial_{x}\left(sv_{x}\left(t,x,0\right)\right)+r,\\
c_{0}\left(z\right) & =c\left(x,z\rightarrow-\infty\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the bulk concentration,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the surfactant concentration,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a source term that measures the flow from the bulk into the surface,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the mean bulk concentration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume both deviation from time averages and the fluid velocities are small,
 therefore amenable to linearization.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{0}$
\end_inset

 be the mean surfactant concentration.
 We further suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $s\left(t,x\right)\propto c\left(t,x,0\right)$
\end_inset

,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta s=\kappa\delta c$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=\partial_{c_{0}}s_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the first order proportion constant (where next order introduces variations).
 We also assume rather homogeneous,
 and strictly static macroscopically,
 bulk,
 so the flux between bulk and surface is diffusion limited:
 
\begin_inset Formula $r=-D\partial_{z}c$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\partial_{t}\delta c & =D\left(\partial_{x}^{2}\delta c+\partial_{z}^{2}\delta c\right),\label{eq:linearized-concentration}\\
\kappa\partial_{t}\delta c\left(t,x,0\right) & =-s_{0}\partial_{x}\left(\partial_{x}\phi\left(t,x,0\right)-\partial_{z}\psi\left(t,x,0\right)\right)-D\partial_{z}\delta c\left(t,x,0\right),\nonumber \\
0 & =\delta c\left(x,z\rightarrow-\infty\right).\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Surface stress
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For an incompressible fluid,
 the stress tensor takes the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{ij} & =-p\delta_{ij}+\rho\nu\left(\partial_{i}q_{j}+\partial_{j}q_{i}\right)\label{eq:fluid-stress}\\
\implies\sigma_{xz} & =\rho\nu\left(\partial_{x}q_{z}+\partial_{z}q_{x}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\rho\nu\left(2\partial_{x}\partial_{z}\phi+\left(\partial_{x}^{2}-\partial_{z}^{2}\right)\psi\right),\nonumber \\
\sigma_{zz} & =-p+2\rho\nu\left(\partial_{z}^{2}\phi+\partial_{x}\partial_{z}\psi\right).\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The elastic equation for the surface is derived thus:
 by conservation of matter and absence of flows,
 the total surfactant mass at each point is constant in time:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
sdA & =dM=const\\
\implies s_{0}dA_{0} & =\left(s_{0}+\delta s\right)\left(dA_{0}+\delta dA\right)\\
\implies\frac{\delta s}{s_{0}} & =-\frac{\delta dA}{dA_{0}},\\
\frac{\partial_{t}s}{s_{0}} & =\frac{\partial_{t}dA}{dA_{0}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The surface tension per unit length at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 is then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T & =T_{0}+k_{e}\delta dA/dA_{0}+k_{v}\frac{\partial_{t}dA}{dA_{0}}\\
 & =T_{0}-k_{e}\frac{\delta s}{s_{0}}-k_{v}\frac{\partial_{t}\delta s}{s_{0}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the film's dilatational elastic constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{v}$
\end_inset

 is the relaxation constant (dilatational viscosity).
 Now if the air above is still (no wind),
 the total force acting tangentially on a unit surfactant area per unit length is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dF}{dy} & =\sigma_{xz}dx-\partial_{x}Tdx\\
\implies\frac{dF}{dA} & =\sigma_{xz}-\partial_{x}T.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This would accelerate the small area of surfactant.
 But at the limit of a thin film,
 the (3D!) mass of this surfactant is small.
 Therefore at normal excitation frequencies (finite accelerations),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dF}{dA}$
\end_inset

 is small,
 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{xz} & =\partial_{x}T\label{eq:shear-at-boundary}\\
 & =-k_{e}s_{0}^{-1}\partial_{x}\delta s-k_{v}s_{0}^{-1}\partial_{x}\partial_{t}\delta s.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly,
 the normal stress at the surface balances the local pull of the water sheet.
 For linear ripples the local slopes are small and we approximate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{zz} & =-p_{0}-\rho g\zeta+T_{0}\partial_{x}^{2}\zeta\label{eq:pressure-at-boundary}\\
 & =-p_{0}-\rho g\int_{-\infty}^{t}\left(\partial_{z}\phi+\partial_{x}\psi\right)dt+T_{0}\int_{-\infty}^{t}\partial_{x}^{2}\left(\partial_{z}\phi+\partial_{x}\psi\right)dt.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The dispersion relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now put in the Fourier ansatz
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi\left(t,x,z\right) & =Ae^{kz}e^{i\left(kx-\omega t\right)},\\
\psi\left(t,x,z\right) & =Be^{mz}e^{i\left(kx-\omega t\right)},\\
\delta c & =Ce^{nz}e^{i\left(kx-\omega t\right)}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

First,
 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:navier-stokes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we immediately find that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-i\omega & =\nu\left(m^{2}-k^{2}\right)\\
\implies m^{2} & =k^{2}-i\frac{\omega}{\nu}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linearized-concentration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-i\omega & =D\left(-k^{2}+n^{2}\right),\nonumber \\
-i\omega\kappa C & =-s_{0}\left(-k^{2}A-imkB\right)-DnC\nonumber \\
\implies n^{2} & =k^{2}-i\frac{\omega}{D},\label{eq:bulk-concentration}\\
C & =\frac{s_{0}\left(k^{2}A+imkB\right)}{Dn-i\omega\kappa}.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shear-at-boundary"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pressure-at-boundary"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{xz} & =-k_{e}\kappa s_{0}^{-1}\partial_{x}\delta c-k_{v}\kappa s_{0}^{-1}\partial_{x}\partial_{t}\delta c\\
 & =Ck\kappa s_{0}^{-1}\left(-ik_{e}-k_{v}\omega\right)e^{i\left(kx-\omega t\right)},\\
\sigma_{zz} & =-p_{0}-\frac{k}{\omega}\left(\rho g+T_{0}k^{2}\right)\left(iA-B\right)e^{i\left(kx-\omega t\right)}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Compare to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fluid-stress"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

,
 plugging 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:navier-stokes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bulk-concentration"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\left(\left(-\frac{k}{\rho\nu}k_{v}-2\right)\omega\kappa-i\left(\frac{k\kappa}{\rho\nu}k_{e}+2Dn\right)\right)k^{2}A\\
 & -\left(\left(-k^{2}-m^{2}\right)\left(Dn-i\omega\kappa\right)-imk\frac{k\kappa}{\rho\nu}\left(-ik_{e}-k_{v}\omega\right)\right)B,\\
\delta pe^{-i\left(kx-\omega t\right)}-\frac{k}{\omega}\left(\rho g+T_{0}k^{2}\right)\left(iA-B\right) & =2\rho\nu\left(k^{2}A+ikmB\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

but from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:navier-stokes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\delta p & =-\rho g\zeta-\rho\partial_{t}\phi\\
\implies\delta pe^{-i\left(kx-\omega t\right)} & =\left(-i\frac{k}{\omega}\rho g+i\omega\rho\right)A+B\frac{k}{\omega}\rho g,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so the normal condition above takes the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\left(2\rho\nu k^{2}-i\omega\rho+2i\frac{k}{\omega}\rho g+i\frac{k^{3}}{\omega}T_{0}\right)A+i\left(2\rho\nu km+i2\frac{k}{\omega}\rho g+i\frac{k^{3}}{\omega}T_{0}\right)B.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We now established an inhomogeneous linear system.
 Dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}k^{3}/\omega$
\end_inset

,
 we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix}0\\
0
\end{pmatrix} & =\begin{pmatrix}\frac{\kappa\left(-\frac{k}{\rho\nu}k_{v}-2\right)\omega^{2}}{T_{0}k}-i\frac{\left(\frac{k\kappa}{\rho\nu}k_{e}+2Dn\right)\omega}{T_{0}k} & \frac{\left(k^{2}+m^{2}\right)\left(Dn-i\omega\kappa\right)\omega}{T_{0}k^{3}}+\frac{i\frac{\kappa}{\rho\nu}\left(k_{v}\omega+ik_{e}\right)m\omega}{T_{0}k}\\
\frac{2\rho\nu}{T_{0}}\frac{\omega}{k}+i\left(\frac{\rho\left(2kg-\omega^{2}\right)}{k^{3}T_{0}}+1\right) & i\left(\frac{2\rho\nu}{T_{0}}\frac{\omega m}{k^{2}}+i\left(\frac{2\rho g}{T_{0}}\frac{1}{k^{2}}+1\right)\right)
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}A\\
B
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This has a nontrivial solution only if the determinant is zero.
\end_layout

